## Description {#details}

Fast multiset implementation for objects that can be identified by small unsigned keys.

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparsemultiset">SparseMultiSet</a> allocates memory proportional to the size of the key universe, so it is not recommended for building composite data structures. It is useful for algorithms that require a single set with fast operations.

Compared to <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/denseset">DenseSet</a> and <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/densemap">DenseMap</a>, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparsemultiset">SparseMultiSet</a> provides constant-time fast <a href="#a2554bf4e6f211e29c3e80fd4c9141c79">clear()</a> as fast as a vector. The <a href="#a007d043f89bfaefaec158a7e93b39832">find()</a>, <a href="#a8586fb88f0c2e2236a1552292cba1dd3">insert()</a>, and <a href="#a3ab390f0c1123852f16664da01de672a">erase()</a> operations are all constant time, and typically faster than a hash table. The iteration order doesn&#39;t depend on numerical key values, it only depends on the order of <a href="#a8586fb88f0c2e2236a1552292cba1dd3">insert()</a> and <a href="#a3ab390f0c1123852f16664da01de672a">erase()</a> operations. Iteration order is the insertion order. Iteration is only provided over elements of equivalent keys, but iterators are bidirectional.

Compared to <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/bitvector">BitVector</a>, SparseMultiSet&lt;unsigned&gt; uses 8x-40x more memory, but offers constant-time <a href="#a2554bf4e6f211e29c3e80fd4c9141c79">clear()</a> and <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/nvptx/nvvmreflect-cpp/#ac934769d93af95250952646a3829df4c">size()</a> operations as well as fast iteration independent on the size of the universe.

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparsemultiset">SparseMultiSet</a> contains a dense vector holding all the objects and a sparse array holding indexes into the dense vector. Most of the memory is used by the sparse array which is the size of the key universe. The SparseT template parameter provides a space/speed tradeoff for sets holding many elements.

When SparseT is uint32&#95;t, <a href="#a007d043f89bfaefaec158a7e93b39832">find()</a> only touches up to 3 cache lines, but the sparse array uses 4 x Universe bytes.

When SparseT is uint8&#95;t (the default), <a href="#a007d043f89bfaefaec158a7e93b39832">find()</a> touches up to 3+&#91;N/256&#93; cache lines, but the sparse array is 4x smaller. N is the number of elements in the set.

For sets that may grow to thousands of elements, SparseT should be set to uint16&#95;t or uint32&#95;t.

Multiset behavior is provided by providing doubly linked lists for values that are inlined in the dense vector. <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparsemultiset">SparseMultiSet</a> is a good choice when one desires a growable number of entries per key, as it will retain the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparseset">SparseSet</a> algorithmic properties despite being growable. Thus, it is often a better choice than a <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparseset">SparseSet</a> of growable containers or a vector of vectors. <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sparsemultiset">SparseMultiSet</a> also keeps iterators valid after erasure (provided the iterators don&#39;t point to the element erased), allowing for more intuitive and fast removal.

<ParametersListItem name="ValueT">The type of objects in the set.</ParametersListItem>

<ParametersListItem name="SparseT">An unsigned integer type. See above.</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

### erase() {#a3ab390f0c1123852f16664da01de672a}

<MemberDefinition
  template={<>template &lt;typename ValueT, typename KeyFunctorT = identity&lt;unsigned&gt;, typename SparseT = uint8&#95;t&gt;</>}
  prototype={<>iterator llvm::SparseMultiSet&lt; ValueT, KeyFunctorT, SparseT &gt;::erase (<a href="#ada97379dfb89c01fb4065e33bf180f0e">iterator</a> I)</>}
  labels = {["inline"]}>
Erases an existing element identified by a valid iterator.

This invalidates iterators pointing at the same entry, but <a href="#a3ab390f0c1123852f16664da01de672a">erase()</a> returns an iterator pointing to the next element in the subset&#39;s list. This makes it possible to erase selected elements while iterating over the subset:

tie(I, E) = Set.equal&#95;range(Key); while (I != E) if (<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/codegen/moduloschedule-cpp/#a106e32122c569cdb42ddf61ecbb0aad1">test(&#42;I)</a>) I = Set.erase(I); else ++I;

Note that if the last element in the subset list is erased, this will return an end iterator which can be decremented to get the new tail (if it exists):

tie(B, I) = Set.equal&#95;range(Key); for (bool isBegin = B == I; !isBegin; /&#42; empty &#42;‍/) &#123; isBegin = (–I) == B; if (<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/codegen/moduloschedule-cpp/#a106e32122c569cdb42ddf61ecbb0aad1">test(I)</a>) break; I = erase(I); &#125;

Definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/sparsemultiset-h/#l00466">466</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/sparsemultiset-h">SparseMultiSet.h</a>.
